        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi> | (<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)</placeName>
                    <date>March 26<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1882</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I write one line to thank you for your last note &amp; your several previous ones, which have interested me much.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I will now get my letter to Nature copied as quickly as I can, &amp; despatch it; but I am at present not very well.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I think that I had better use the old name of Cyclas.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Yours very faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 (<hi rend="italic">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)] <hi rend="italic">parentheses added</hi> </note>
            </div>
            
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13738.xml">letter from W. D. Crick, 24 March 1882</ref>. Crick first wrote to CD about his discovery of a small clam adhering to the leg of a water beetle in his letter of <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13692.xml">18 February 1882</ref>; he wrote four more letters on the subject and sent the specimens to CD (see Crick’s letters of <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13705.xml">24 February 1882</ref>, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13715.xml">3 March 1882</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13721.xml">9 March 1882</ref>). CD mentioned being very unwell for several days in his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13722.xml">letter to W. D. Crick, 10 March [1882]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD’s article, <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_11721.xml">‘Dispersal of freshwater bivalves’</ref>, was published in <hi rend="italic">Nature</hi>, 6 April 1882, pp. 529–30.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Crick had referred to his specimen as <hi rend="italic">Sphaerium corneum</hi>; <hi rend="italic">Cyclas cornea</hi>, a synonym, is the name CD used in his article. For more on the names, see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13738.xml">letter from W. D. Crick, 24 March 1882</ref> and n. 1.</note>    
        </div>
    
